\fs48 \cf5 Common.js Modules\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf5 Node.js comes with built-in support for modules. These are not the same as ES2015 modules; these are called Common.js modules and have a syntax that makes use of the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 require
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 ,\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 module
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 , and\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 exports
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0keywords. In Common.js, every JavaScript file is a module. Since we are not using\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 <script>
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0tags (as we are not in the browser), we need a way of loading JavaScript from one file to another, and modules are our answer.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl380\sa200

\fs36 \cf5 Module Exports\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf5 Let's take a look at some examples using Node.js modules. Create a file called\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 helpers.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 , which will export some data to another file called\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 main.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 . In our\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 helpers.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 , let's add the following:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf5 \cb9 module.exports = \{\
  \cf11 name\cf5 : \cf10 "Elie"\cf5 ,\
  sayHi() \{\
    console.log(`Hi 
\f4\b \cf12 $
\f3\b0 \cf5 \{\cf13 this\cf5 .name\}!`);\
  \}\
\};\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 Now in our\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 main.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 , let's add the following:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf5 \cb9 const helpers = require(\cf10 "./helpers"\cf5 );\
helpers.sayHi();\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 If we run\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 node main.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0we should see the text "Hi Elie!" in the console. So how have we done this? We used the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 module.exports
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0object to send an object from one file (
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 helpers.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 ) to another (
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 main.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 ).\
To import the module we use the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 require
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0keyword followed by the name of a module. Notice that no\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 .js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0is needed to reference the file because it is assumed to be a\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 .js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0file by default.\
Also notice that we are using a\'a0
\f2\b relative
\f0\b0 \'a0path here (i.e. we have to include\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 ./
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 ). This is\'a0
\f2\b very
\f0\b0 \'a0important, because if we do not use a relative path, Node will assume you're referencing a built-in module or a package. When you are using your own modules,\'a0
\f2\b always
\f0\b0 \'a0use relative paths.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl380\sa200

\fs36 \cf5 Exports Shorthand\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf5 Let's make a file called\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 moreHelpers.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0and let's use the\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 exports
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0syntax.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf5 \cb9 exports.
\f4\b \cf14 sayHello
\f3\b0 \cf5  = 
\f4\b \cf0 function
