\f0\fs36 \cf5 \cb1 Using Index Files\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\fs28 \cf5 A nice benefit to using Common.js files is utilizing index files. In any folder, you may have a file named\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 index.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 , which lets you reference its parent folder instead of the actual file itself. In other words, these two syntaxes are equivalent:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f4\b\fs26 \cf0 \cb9 var
\f3\b0 \cf5  models = require(\cf10 "./models/index"\cf5 ); 
\f5\i \cf15 // /index is not necessary in a folder
\f3\i0 \cf5 \

\f4\b \cf0 var
\f3\b0 \cf5  models = require(\cf10 "./models"\cf5 );\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 When building larger apps, you can leverage this advantage by having your\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 index.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0files\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 require
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0everything in their folder and then export a big object to the main file.\
Say, for example, we have a\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 models
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0folder with three files in it:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf5 \cb9 models/\
  first.js\
  second.js\
  third.js\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 We can create an index file that just exports those three for convenient imports everywhere else:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\i \cf5 models/index.js
\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf5 \cb9 exports.first = require(\cf10 "./first"\cf5 );\
exports.second = require(\cf10 "./second"\cf5 );\
exports.third = require(\cf10 "./third"\cf5 );\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 Then in our\'a0
\f3\fs26 \cf7 \cb8 main.js
\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 \'a0file, we can import everything easily:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\i \cf5 main.js
\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl360

\f3\fs26 \cf5 \cb9 const \{ first, second, third \} = require(\cf10 "./models"\cf5 );\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl500\sa400

\f0\fs28 \cf5 \cb1 Which makes large application code pretty clean!\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl380\sa200

